<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-676-367  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 676 367.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Nov 1 1990 v29 n21 p21(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>James Ready on: real-time standards. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ready, James F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Real-time system developers will benefit considerably from thedevelopment of standards for a reference model of layeredinterfaces and a standard set of application-oriented workloadsfor evaluating the suitability of real-time systems for specificapplications.andP;  A proposed real-time computing reference model ispresented made up of seven layers: the physical or mechanicallayer; the hardware layer, which has low-level signal andhigh-level programmable sublayers; basic services, which are madeup of a BIOS, a program loading interface and a low-leveldebugging interface; the kernel layer interface for lightweightconcurrency; the process layer corresponding to themultiprogramming level of concurrency in time-sharing operatingsystems; the virtual machine layer, which presents a computingmodel for application programmers; and the application-specificprogramming level.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Real-Time SystemsSystem DesignStandardsModels of ComputationApplications ProgrammingSoftware DesignStandardization.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A sample reference model for real-time system standards. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>